|20,74
     A function call may be used in expressions to obtain the value of the
function.  The type of value returned by the function must be appropriate
in the expression that contains the function call.  For example, if a func-
tion returns an integer value, you can only call the function in expres-
sions where an integer value is legal.
     To call a function in an expression, simply type the name of the func-
tion.  If the function takes arguments, put the arguments in parentheses
immediately following the function name.  If you do not enter any arguments
for the function, ALICE will put in appropriate placeholders indicating
what kind of arguments are necessary.  If you delete the argument list, you
can get it back by moving the cursor to the function name and pressing "(".

Function Call Examples:
     x := sin(y);
     if eoln then begin ...
     while not eof(intfile) do begin ...
|mFor more, choose
|iDo nothing,nop
